📜 The Core Tenets of the LCES Charter
The charter formalizes the "v18 reality" you described: that the value lies in the human-driven iterations, not the initial output.

1. The Supremacy of the Strategist
- Doctrine: AI agents (Architect, Builder, Inspector) are "sub-processors." Only the human Strategist possesses the authority to validate, interpret, and sign off on a work product.
- Educational Goal: To train the Strategist to identify legal nuances that AI often flattens, such as the difference between a "fact" and a "post-hoc characterization."
1. The Multi-Agent "Adversarial" Feedback Loop
- The Architect: Focuses on structural integrity and procedural adherence.
- The Builder: Generates content and expands on evidence "anchors."
- The Inspector: Plays the role of the critic, identifying gaps, hallucinations, or logical leaps.
- The Human: Acts as the high court, weighing the input of all three agents to reach a final determination.
1. Iteration as Proof of Competence
The charter recognizes that a v18 document is inherently more "procedural" than a v1. This versioning tracks the evolution of the Strategist's own understanding. It serves as an audit trail of:
- Refinement: Where the human corrected the AI's course.
- Grounding: How specific evidence (emails, dates, records) was tied to the narrative.
- Strategy: How the theory of the case was hardened against the Inspector's challenges.
🎓 Moving from Generator to Craft
By adhering to the LCES Charter, you ensure that the system remains an educational instrument. You aren't asking the AI to "win a case"; you are using the AI to build the intellectual muscle required to understand the case yourself.
This approach effectively bypasses the pitfalls of "AI-generated law" by keeping the human at the center of the calculus—where the AI provides the calculation, but the human provides the logic.
